The natural strength, and poverty of their country—the ac- cession of emigrating nobles, from other provinces—and the valour inspired by the reflection, that it was their last re·- treat, enabled them to make a powerful stand. For many centur-ies, they remained a sovereign people, and have, to this day, preserved a language, essentially different from the German, though under few obligations to the Latin. This can be no other than the Celtic of their progenitors.
